03/06/2022 1:17 PM EST

Update: A fresh taste of winter looms for East Tennessee

By Ben Garrett
Share
Facebook
Twitter
Pinterest
WhatsApp

    Rain, then cold…then snow?!?

    Yes, yes…and maybe.

    As we previously noted, the beautiful stretch of early spring weather we’ve been enjoying is about to come to an end. Today is the last day with temps in the 70s, and rain will return on Monday, with another round of rain Tuesday night into early Wednesday.

    The rain, and some possible thunderstorms, will be accompanying a cold front. Of course, this is the time of year when anytime we talk about a cold front, we have to talk about the possibility of severe weather, and the Storm Prediction Center does have most of Tennessee — including our area — under a Slight Risk for severe weather on Monday, with damaging wind gusts being the primary threat.

    Temps will fall through the day on Monday, and we’ll be quite a bit colder behind the front. But not too cold, initially. We’ll only be in the low 50s on Tuesday, and although that’s almost 20° cooler than we have been the last several days, it’s actually right about normal for this time of year. And we’ll be back to 60° by Thursday.

    But another, more potent cold front will sweep through at the end of the week, and that’s what will deliver a real shot of cold to our area.

    Whereas the first cold front on Monday will feature pre-frontal precipitation, the second cold front on Friday will feature post-frontal precipitation. That means the precipitation will follow the frontal boundary, which means it will be in the form of snow if temperatures are cold enough … and it does look like temps will be cold enough.

    In fact, the GFS model currently takes us into the upper teens both Saturday and Sunday mornings. The ECMWF model is a little warmer initially, only taking us into the mid 20s on Saturday morning, but by Sunday morning it has us in the teens as well.

    For now, the National Weather Service’s forecast has a low of 24° for Friday night, with a slight chance of rain or snow.

    The next question will be just how much precipitation falls, and whether accumulating snow is a possibility. The GFS is showing accumulating snow for the northern Cumberland Plateau, but that seems really unlikely — except for maybe a little slushy accumulation on grassy surfaces. Ground temps will be quite warm, and precipitation amounts should be relatively limited.

    For now, it’s something that bears watching as we move through the week ahead. The main storyline is that it’s getting ready to get really cold again for a few days, regardless of whether there is any snow flying. In fact, the high temp is forecasted to be only in the mid 30s on Saturday, which is about 20° below average for this time of year.

    Fortunately, the cold snap won’t last long, and there are currently no replenishing shots of cold air showing up, as it looks like a return to at least slightly above-average temperatures will return the following week.

    Eye to the Sky is a weather blog of the Independent Herald, written primarily by IH publisher Ben Garrett. Views expressed here are those of the authors and should not be considered substitute for official advisories, watches or warnings from the National Weather Service. For the latest, most up-to-date forecast information, see weather.gov/mrx.
